04224nam a22005535i 9780804779159DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20202011cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047791597 a10.1515/97808047791592doi  a(DE-B1597)564818  a(OCoLC)1178769695  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aKF2994.M399 2011 7aLAW0500002bisacsh04a346.7304/821 aMazzone, Jason, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCopyfraud and Other Abuses of Intellectual Property Law /cJason Mazzone. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tChapter 1. Copyfraud -- tChapter 2. Vanishing fair use -- tChapter 3. Samples and Mash-ups -- tChapter 4. Takedowns and lockups -- tChapter 5. From copyright to contract -- tChapter 6. The ownerless society -- tChapter 7. Trademarks unbound -- tChapter 8. Copyfraud liability -- tChapter 9. Defending copyright fair use -- tChapter 10. Putting intellectual property in its place -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIntellectual property law in the United States does not work well and it needs to be reformed-but not for the reasons given by most critics. The issue is not that intellectual property rights are too easily obtained, too broad in scope, and too long in duration. Rather, the primary problem is overreaching by publishers, producers, artists, and others who abuse intellectual property law by claiming stronger rights than the law actually gives them. From copyfraud-like phony copyright notices attached to the U.S. Constitution-to lawsuits designed to prevent people from poking fun at Barbie, from controversies over digital sampling in hip-hop to Major League Baseball's ubiquitous restriction on sharing any "accounts and descriptions of this game," overreaching claims of intellectual property rights are everywhere. Overreaching interferes with legitimate uses and reproduction of a wide variety of works, imposes enormous social and economic costs, and ultimately undermines creative endeavors. As this book reveals, the solution is not to change the scope or content of intellectual property rights, but to create mechanisms to prevent people asserting rights beyond those they legitimately possess. While there are many other books on intellectual property, this is the first to examine overreaching as a distinct problem and to show how to solve it. Jason Mazzone makes a series of timely proposals by which government, organizations, and ordinary people can stand up to creators and content providers when they seek to grab more than the law gives them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aCopyrightxUnited States. 0aCopyrightzUnited States. 0aFair use (Copyright)xUnited States. 0aFair use (Copyright)zUnited States. 0aIntellectual propertyxUnited States. 0aIntellectual propertyzUnited States. 7aLAW / Intellectual Property / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080477915940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804779159423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804779159.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles